Inngest function.tsx:
> Defined an AI agent named `AiCareerChatAgent` using `createAgent`.
> Configured the agent to use Google's `gemini-2.0-flash-lite` model via API key from environment variables.
> Left the `system` prompt blank — this can later be used to define tone, behavior, or specific instructions for the AI.
> Created a serverless function `AiCareerAgent` using `inngest.createFunction`.
> This function listens for the event named `AiCareerAgent`.
> When triggered, the function extracts `userInput` from the event payload.
> The `userInput` is passed to the `AiCareerChatAgent.run()` method to get an AI-generated response.
> The result from the agent is returned as the function’s output.
> Avoided referencing `AiCareerAgent` inside itself to prevent circular reference errors in TypeScript.
> This separation of agent logic and event function makes the system modular and scalable.

API:ai-career-chat-agent:route: 
> Defined a `POST` API route to receive user input for AI processing.
> Extracted `userInput` from the request body using `await req.json()`.
> Used `inngest.send()` to trigger the `AiCareerAgent` function with `userInput` as event data.
> Retrieved the first `runId` from the returned IDs to track the status of the AI job.
> Used a `while(true)` loop to continuously poll the run status from Inngest until it reports `Completed`.
> Implemented a short delay (`500ms`) between polling requests using `setTimeout` to avoid spamming the server.
> Once completed, returned the final run status using `NextResponse.json()`.
> Created a helper function `getRuns(runId)` to fetch the run status from Inngest’s REST API.
> Used `axios.get()` to call the Inngest `runs` API endpoint with the proper Bearer authorization header.
> Secured sensitive values (`INNGEST_SERVER_HOST` and `INNGEST_SIGNING_KEY`) using environment variables.
> This flow helps wait for a long-running AI process to finish before responding to the client.
